{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605626"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15870"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.09,0,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4663"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7031"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20550"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELichen sclerosus is a chronic inflammatory condition that typically affects the anogenital region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about lichen sclerosus is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Affects only prepubertal girls","Complete cure is achieved with one course of topical steroids","Has no risk of malignant transformation","Occurs exclusively in men","Requires long-term monitoring due to cancer risk"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELichen sclerosus is a chronic inflammatory condition that primarily affects the anogenital region. \u003Cstrong\u003EAffecting only prepubertal girls\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it can occur at any age, though it is most common in postmenopausal women. \u003Cstrong\u003EComplete cure with one course of topical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it is a chronic condition requiring ongoing treatment and monitoring. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaving no risk of malignant transformation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as there is a 3-5% lifetime risk of developing vulvar cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EOccurring exclusively in men\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it predominantly affects women. \u003Cstrong\u003ERequiring long-term monitoring due to cancer risk\u003C/strong\u003E is correct due to the pre-malignant nature of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition is managed with potent topical corticosteroids and requires regular follow-up to monitor for complications and malignant transformation. Patients should be educated about the chronic nature of the condition and the importance of adherence to treatment and follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lichen sclerosus is a chronic inflammatory condition affecting the anogenital region that can progress to vulvar cancer in 3-5% of cases","First-line treatment is potent topical corticosteroids with regular long-term follow-up","The condition primarily affects postmenopausal women but can occur at any age"],"references":["De Luca DA, Papara C, Vorobyev A, Staiger H, Bieber K, Tha\u00e7i D, Ludwig RJ. Lichen sclerosus: The 2023 update. Front Med (Lausanne). 2023 Feb 16;10:1106318. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2023.1106318. PMID: 36873861; PMCID: PMC9978401.","Kirtschig G. Lichen Sclerosus-Presentation, Diagnosis and Management. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2016 May 13;113(19):337-43. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2016.0337. PMID: 27232363; PMCID: PMC4904529.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48408"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T13:20:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T13:20:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synony